name: 4-methylcyclohexene
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The basic unit, cyclohexane, has a melting point of 6.5°C. The presence of a double bond in cyclohexene typically lowers the melting point significantly due to less efficient packing, which could decrease the melting point by approximately 120°C. The addition of a methyl group increases the melting point as it adds van der Waals forces, slightly increasing the melting point by about 5°C.
